This turns out to be almost a “hello-world”-level program once you strip away all of the bogus branches, the empty-string tricks and the two‐letter helper functions.  Here is the core of what it does:

1.  It defines an array of the seven three‐letter day-of-week abbreviations in order  
        String[] s = { "SUN","MON","TUE","WED","THU","FRI","SAT" };  
2.  It reads a single token from stdin (e.g. “MON”, “FRI”, etc.).  
3.  It walks through that array with an index i from 0 to 6, looking for the entry that equals the input string.  
4.  As soon as it finds a match it breaks out of the loop.  
5.  Finally it prints `7 – i` and exits.  

So if you input “MON” (which is at index 1) it prints 6, if you input “SAT” (index 6) it prints 1, if you input “SUN” (index 0) it prints 7, etc.  

All the calls to  
   `Main.l(...)`, `Main.ll(...)`, `"" .length()`, bit‐twiddling branches that never fire, empty `return;`s, etc., are pure dead‐code or control‐flow obfuscation.  The “FastReader” inner class is just an over‐obfuscated but functionally standard fast I/O routine.  

If you clean everything up, you get roughly:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
  Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
  String[] days = {"SUN","MON","TUE","WED","THU","FRI","SAT"};
  String today = in.next();
  int i = 0;
  while (i < 7 && !today.equals(days[i])) {
    i++;
  }
  System.out.println(7 - i);
}
```

In short: “read a weekday, find its index in SUN,MON,…,SAT, and print 7 minus that index.”

This code actually boils down to two pieces:

  1. A “fast I/O”‐style tokenizer/reader called class `hayami`
  2. A `Main` that reads an array of integers and counts how many times you see a new maximum as you scan from left to right.

All of the bizarre `hayami.ll(...)`, `hayami.Ill(...)`, `"" .length()` tricks, dead‐code `if("  ".length()==0)` blocks, and one‐letter method names like `lIl`, `IIl`, etc., are purely there to confuse you.  Underneath, they’re just:

  • comparisons like ``, `>=`, `==`, `!=`  
  • calls to `InputStream.read(...)` into a buffer  
  • loops that skip whitespace, read tokens, parse ints/longs/doubles  
  • dead branches that never execute or never change program state.

If you strip away all of that obfuscation, you get:

--- Class hayami (the reader) ---
• hasNextByte()  
• readByte() → next raw byte or –1  
• isPrintableAscii(byte b) → b ∈ [33..126]  
• skipWhitespace()  
• nextToken() → `String` of printable ASCII up to next whitespace  
• nextLong() → parses an optional `-` and digits into a `long`  
• nextInt() → calls nextLong() and checks range  
• nextDouble() → `Double.parseDouble(nextToken())`

(plus a trivial `close()` that shuts `System.in`)

--- Main.main(...) ---
1. hayami in = new hayami();  
2. int n = in.nextInt();  
3. int[] h = new int[n];  
4. for (i = 0; i  currentMax) {  
       ans++;  
       currentMax = h[i];  
     }  
   }  
7. System.out.println(ans);  
   in.close();

Behaviorally it reads an array `h[0..n-1]` and prints the number of times `h[i]` strictly exceeds all previously seen values. In other words, it counts the “record‐breaking” elements in the sequence.

All of the extra methods and empty‐string length checks are just dead code or aliasing for simple comparisons, inserted to make the control flow look much more complex than it really is.

The easiest way to see through all of the “weird” method‐calls and dead branches is to rewrite the comparisons in plain Java and then collapse the chains of if–else.  Once you do that the program boils down to

1.  read an integer N  
2.  set a flag `ans = false`  
3.  if (N>3 && N≠5 && N≠6 && N≠9) {  
4.    &nbsp;&nbsp;if (N==10) {  
5.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// do nothing (ans stays false)  
6.    &nbsp;&nbsp;}  
7.    &nbsp;&nbsp;else if (N%7==0)                ans = true;  
8.    &nbsp;&nbsp;else if (N%4==0)                ans = true;  
9.    &nbsp;&nbsp;else if (N%7 % 4 == 0)          ans = true;   // i.e. N%7==0 or 4  
10.   &nbsp;&nbsp;else if (N%8 % 7 == 0             // N%8==0 or 7  
11.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;|| (N%14)%4==0)       ans = true;  
12.   &nbsp;&nbsp;else if ((N%12)%7==0             // N%12==0 or 7  
13.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;|| (N%21)%4==0)       ans = true;  
14.   &nbsp;&nbsp;else if ((N%16)%7==0             // N%16==0,7,14  
15.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;|| (N%20)%7==0       // N%20==0,7,14  
16.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;|| (N%24)%7==0)       ans = true;  
17.  }  
18.  print (ans ? "Yes" : "No");  

Everything else in the original is purely obfuscation (the single‐character method names I, Il, ll, IIl, etc. simply stand for >, ==, ==0, !=0, etc., and the `"".length()` checks plus impossible `if` s are there to bloat the bytecode).  

In English:  
• If N≤3, or N is exactly 5, 6, 9 or 10, the answer is “No.”  
• Otherwise you go through a cascade of remainder checks—if N is divisible by 7 or 4, or N mod 7=4, or N mod 8 is 0 or 7, or N mod 14 is one of {0,4,8,12}, or N mod 12 is {0,7}, or N mod 21∈{0,4,8,12,16,20}, or N mod 16∈{0,7,14}, or N mod 20∈{0,7,14}, or N mod 24∈{0,7,14,21}—then we set ans to true.  
• Finally we print “Yes” if any of those conditions held, or “No” otherwise.  

That is the entire behavior of the program once you strip away the dead‐code injections.

This program really boils down to a single simple check:

1. It reads one token (as a Java `String`) from standard input.
2. If that token is exactly `"ABC"`, it prints  
     ARC  
   otherwise it prints  
     ABC  

All of the extra methods (`I`, `l`, `Il`, `lIl`, the weird `if ("".length())` lines, the pointless `""`‐and‐`" ".length()` checks, the unused branches, etc.) are just obfuscated dead‐code camouflage.  Underneath, the only branch that ever matters is:

    String s = in.String();
    if (s.equals("ABC")) {
      out.println("ARC");
    } else {
      out.println("ABC");
    }

Everything else in `InputReader` is just a standard fast‐IO implementation wrapped in a bunch of redundant boolean helpers to thwart easy reading of the control flow.

This code is simply a heavily-obfuscated implementation of two things:

  1.  A “FastScanner” for tokenizing input (integers, longs, doubles, strings) almost exactly like you’d find in many competitive‐programming templates.
  2.  A `main` method that reads three integers N, A, B and computes

         ans = ∑_{i=1…N} [ A ≤ digitSum(i) ≤ B ] · i

    i.e. it adds up every i from 1 to N whose sum of decimal digits lies between A and B (inclusive), then prints the total.

All of the apparent complexity (and “dead” code) is just control‐flow obfuscation:

  •  Every comparison (``, `>=`, `==`, `!=`) is wrapped in a tiny static helper function with a two‐letter name (e.g.  
     lIl, llIl, IIl, etc.).  
  •  Everywhere you see  
       "".length();  
     or  
       if ("foo".length() < 0) {...}  
     or  
       if (null == null) continue;  
     these are no‐ops or branches that are either always taken or never taken—they inject “dead code” to confuse static analysis.  
  •  There are unused methods in `Main` (gcd, lcm, isPrime) which are never called from `main`—again, just noise.

If you strip away all of that, the logic is exactly:

  FastScanner sc = new FastScanner();
  int N = sc.nextInt();
  int A = sc.nextInt();
  int B = sc.nextInt();
  long ans = 0;
  for (int i = 1; i <= N; i++) {
      int s = sumOfDigits(i);
      if (A <= s && s <= B) {
          ans += i;
      }
  }
  System.out.println(ans);

where `sumOfDigits(i)` is implemented by manually extracting each decimal digit.  The final `else if (i == 10000)` branch just handles the one remaining case if N can be 10000 (sum of digits of 10000 is 1), so it too adds `i` to the answer if `A ≤ 1 ≤ B`.

In short, once you collapse all of the dummy branches and rename the comparison helpers to their real operators, you get the familiar “sum all i from 1 to N whose digit‐sum lies in [A,B]” solution.

This little program can look terrifying at first—dozens of nested loops, strange `if ("".length())` checks, dummy `while`-loops that never exit, and tiny helper methods with names like `I`, `l`, `Il`, `ll`, etc.  The vast majority of that is pure dead-code / control-flow junk designed to defeat naive decompilation and human eyeballing.  In fact, none of the interesting routines (`cin()`, `split()`, `kMarsh()`, etc.) ever get called.  

If you strip away all of the bogus loops and methods you discover that the only thing the program actually does is in `main`:

  • Read a single line from standard input and parse it as a `double l`.  
  • Compute Math.pow(l/3.0, 3.0)  (i.e. (l/3)³).  
  • Print that result.  

Everything else in the source is just noise.  The real functionality is:

    // real main logic
    double l = Double.valueOf(br.readLine());
    System.out.println( Math.pow(l/3.0, 3.0) );

All of the other code is never reached (or never invoked) and exists only to make static/dynamic analysis harder.

The easiest way to see past all of the bogus branches and empty‐string “length()” tricks is to collapse each of the tiny comparison methods back into plain Java operators and ignore any branch that can never fire.  Once you do that, the heart of the program (the `solve()` method) becomes:

1. Read two integers, `n` and `m`.
2. Read an array `a` of length `m`.
3. Compute the sum `s` of all elements in `a`.
4. If `s > n`, print `-1`.
5. Otherwise print `n - s`.

All of the rest of the code is just:

– A fast I/O skeleton (methods to read bytes, skip whitespace, parse `int`, `long`, `double`, strings, arrays, etc.),  
– A bunch of one‐line static methods like  
    • `I(x,y)` which returns `x  y`  
    • `Il(x)` which returns `x != 0`  
    • …and so on,  
– Numerous dead‐code branches that look like
```java
"".length();
if (-" ".length()  n) {
    print(-1);
} else {
    print(n - s);
}
```

In other words the program checks whether the sum of `m` values exceeds a budget `n`.  If it does, it outputs `-1`; otherwise it outputs how much of the budget remains.

The easiest way to see what this program actually does is to strip away all of the “dead‐code” tricks (the empty strings, the weird bitwise-always-true guards, the pointless helper methods with names like I, ll, IIl, etc.) and rewrite the core loop in plain Java.  Once you do that, you end up with something like this:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
  Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
  String s = in.next();
  for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
    // even index (0,2,4,…), character must NOT be 'L'
    if (i % 2 == 0 && s.charAt(i) == 'L') {
      System.out.println("No");
      return;
    }
    // odd index (1,3,5,…), character must NOT be 'R'
    if (i % 2 == 1 && s.charAt(i) == 'R') {
      System.out.println("No");
      return;
    }
  }
  System.out.println("Yes");
}
```

In other words:

1. Read a single string `s` from standard input.
2. Walk through its characters by 0-based index `i`.
3. If you ever find an `'L'` in an even position or an `'R'` in an odd position, immediately print `"No"` and exit.
4. If you finish the loop without finding any violation, print `"Yes"`.

All of the other methods (`gcd`, `lcm`, and the dozens of tiny boolean helpers like `I(a)`, `ll(n,m)`, `IIl(x,y)`, etc.), the pointless `"" .length()` calls, the impossible‐to‐hit branches, the complicated `FastReader`, etc., are pure obfuscation—they don’t change the fact that the program is simply enforcing the rule:

   “Characters at even indices must not be ‘L’; characters at odd indices must not be ‘R’.”

The easiest way to understand what this program is doing is to strip away all of the dead‐code / bogus checks and rename the tiny comparison functions back to their obvious meanings.  Once you do that, you end up with something like:

```java
public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
    int a = sc.nextInt();
    int b = sc.nextInt();
    int c = sc.nextInt();

    // count how many i in [a..b] exactly divide c
    int count = 0;
    for (int i = a; i <= b; i++) {
      if (c % i == 0) {
        count++;
      }
    }

    // only print if inputs are in the expected 1..10000 range and a <= b
    if (1 <= a && a <= 10_000 &&
        1 <= b && b <= 10_000 &&
        1 <= c && c <= 10_000 &&
        a <= b) {
      System.out.println(count);
    }
  }
}
```

Everything else in the original is just “fake” control flow (empty `"".length()` tricks, always‐false ifs, nonsense bitwise comparisons) injected to confuse anyone reading the code.  The real work is:

  • Read three integers `a`, `b`, `c`.  
  • Loop `i` from `a` up to `b`.  
  • Whenever `c % i == 0` increment a counter.  
  • Finally (if the inputs satisfy 1≤a,b,c≤10000 and a≤b) print the count.

Let me first strip away all of the junk and look at the two big if–branches.  Almost every extra line is either  

  1. a no–op (e.g. `"".length()`),  
  2. a bogus boolean check that never really fires, or  
  3. an `I(x,y)` call which is just `return x==y;`.  

Once you remove those, you get something like this (I’ve reordered some lines for clarity):

```
int N = sc.nextInt();
int sum = 0;
int a;

// branch 1: hundreds‐digit == 1
if ((N/100) == 1) {
  sum += 900;        // 9 * 100
  a = N - 100;       // strip off the hundreds place
  int t = a/10;      // the tens digit

  if (t == 1) {
    sum +=  90;      // 9 * 10
    a   -= 10;       // strip off the tens place, left with units
    int u = a;       // the ones digit
    if (u == 1)       sum +=   9;  // 9 * 1
    else if (u == 9)  sum +=   1;  // 1 * 1
  }
  else if (t == 9) {
    sum +=  10;      // 1 * 10
    a   -= 90;       // strip off the tens place
    int u = a;       // the ones digit
    if (u == 1)       sum +=   9;
    else if (u == 9)  sum +=   1;
  }
}

// branch 2: hundreds‐digit == 9
if ((N/100) == 9) {
  sum += 100;        // 1 * 100
  a = N - 900;       // strip off the hundreds place
  int t = a/10;      // the tens digit

  if (t == 1) {
    sum +=  90;      // 9 * 10
    a   -= 10;
    int u = a;
    if (u == 1)       sum +=   9;
    else if (u == 9)  sum +=   1;
  }
  else if (t == 9) {
    sum +=  10;      // 1 * 10
    a   -= 90;
    int u = a;
    if (u == 1)       sum +=   9;
    else if (u == 9)  sum +=   1;
  }
}

System.out.println(sum);
```

What this is really doing is a very convoluted “swap every 1↔9” on the hundreds, tens, and units—but only if the digit above it was also a 1 or 9.  Concretely:

  • If the 100’s digit is 1, it adds 9×100 to `sum`.  
  • If the 100’s digit is 9, it adds 1×100 to `sum`.  
  • Then it peels off that digit, looks at the 10’s place:  
     – if it is 1, it adds 9×10;  
     – if it is 9, it adds 1×10;  
     – otherwise it skips the unit‐digit check altogether.  
  • Finally it peels off the tens place, looks at the units place:  
     – if it is 1, it adds 9×1;  
     – if it is 9, it adds 1×1;  
     – otherwise nothing more happens.  

All of the `I(a,b)`, `"".length()`, the XORs and string‐comparison returns are simply dead‐code injected to confuse static analyzers.  The net effect is:  

  – Inputs whose hundreds digit is neither 1 nor 9 yield 0.  
  – For 100…199 it “flips” each contiguous 1 or 9 from the left into a 9 or 1 respectively, weighted by place‐value.  
  – For 900…999 it does the same flip but starting from a 9‐hundreds.  

Examples:  
  – N=111 → 9*100 + 9*10 + 9*1 = 999  
  – N=119 → 9*100 + 9*10 + 1*1 = 991  
  – N=191 → 9*100 + 1*10 + 9*1 = 919  
  – N=999 → 1*100 + 1*10 + 1*1 = 111  
  – N=123 → hundreds=1 so sum=900, tens=2 (neither 1 nor 9) so stop → prints 900  
  – N=500 → neither branch → prints 0  

In short, under all of the fluff the code is just checking each digit (only in the 1xx or 9xx ranges), and if it sees a 1 it adds 9×place‐value, if it sees a 9 it adds 1×place‐value, otherwise it stops processing lower digits. The rest is purely obfuscation.

At its heart, this “mammoth” of an input‐/output wrapper plus stringy dead‐paths boils down to exactly three lines of real logic in main(…):

    int x   = in.Int();
    int ans = 0;

    // exchange every 500‐unit chunk for 1000
    if (x >= 500) {
      int blocks = x / 500;
      ans += blocks * 1000;
      x   -= blocks * 500;
    }

    // exchange every remaining 5‐unit chunk for 5
    if (x >= 5) {
      int fiveBlocks = x / 5;
      ans += fiveBlocks * 5;
      // x   -= fiveBlocks * 5;   // pointless after this line
    }

    out.println(ans);

In math form the program prints:

    floor(x/500) * 1000  +  floor((x % 500)/5) * 5

and nothing more.  Every other class and method you see is purely scaffolding and control‐flow obfuscation:

  • A custom InputReader with a dozen one-letter methods named Il, ll, lIl, IIl, etc., each just wrapping simple integer tests (==, >=, !=, ≤, etc.).  
  • A mix of `"" .length()` calls, empty‐string comparisons and dead branches (`if ("  ".length() ≥ "   ".length()) …`) that never change state.  
  • A full OutputWriter wrapper around PrintWriter that only ever gets used to flush a single integer.

All of that is noise—dead code or needless indirection.  Remove it and you’re left with a tiny routine that:

1. Reads an integer `x`.  
2. Converts as many 500-unit “coins” as possible into 1000 units each.  
3. Converts as many 5-unit coins from the remainder into 5 units each.  
4. Prints the total “returned” amount.

Description_Simple.comparison_text:
Title: Binary‐String Cancellation Counter

Main goal: This code reads a numeric string (typically of ‘0’ and ‘1’), builds a custom doubly‐linked‐list “stack” by scanning the string from right to left, and applies a simple cancellation rule: 
- if the next digit equals the current top, push it onto the list; 
- if it differs, either pop one element (if the list has more than one) or reset the list (when it has exactly one);
after processing all digits it counts the remaining nodes and prints the number of “deleted” digits (original length minus remaining list size).  
Custom helper methods (I, Il, IIl, ll, etc.) merely wrap basic comparisons to obscure the logic.

Description_Vague.comparison_text:
The quickest way to see through the noise is to strip away the “dummy” methods and the dead‐code injections (the `""​.length()` calls, the bogus `if`-tests that can never be true, the random bit-twiddling constants etc.) and look at the one real thing that `Main.solve()` is doing:

1. It reads a single token as a `String` (via `in.nextStr()`).
2. It walks the string from left to right, comparing each character to its predecessor.
3. If any two adjacent characters are the same, it immediately prints  
        Bad  
   and returns.
4. If it makes it all the way to the end with no two consecutive characters equal, it prints  
        Good  

All of the rest—the six or seven static methods in `FastScanner` (named things like `I()`, `Il()`, `ll()`, `lll()`, …), the no-op `""​.length()` calls after every read, the impossible `if` blocks that never fire, the redundant bitwise constants—is just control-flow obfuscation. Underneath it all:

– `FastScanner.nextStr()` is a normal “skip whitespace, read until next whitespace or EOF” routine.  
– `Main.solve()` boils down to

  ```
  String s = nextStr();
  for (int i = 1; i < s.length(); i++) {
    if (s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(i-1)) {
      print("Bad");
      return;
    }
  }
  print("Good");
  ```

That’s the entire real functionality.

This “Main” class actually boils down to a very simple routine once you strip away all of the fake branches, the dead‐code guards like  
```
"".length();
if ("  ".length() > 0) …
```
and the decoy methods (gcd, lcm, func, all of which are never called).  Everything else is noise or an obfuscated fast‐reader.

Here is the real behavior of main, in pseudocode:

1. Read two tokens from stdin (call them nStr and mStr).
2. Parse them as integers N = Integer.parseInt(nStr) and M = Integer.parseInt(mStr).
3. Compare N and M:
   • if (N < M)  
       • repeat the string nStr, M times  
       • e.g. if nStr=”3” and M=5, build “33333”  
   • else  
       • repeat the string mStr, N times  
       • e.g. if nStr=”5”, mStr=”2” (so N=5, M=2, N≥M) build “22” repeated 5 times → “22222”
4. Print that repeated‐string and exit.

In other words:  
– We take the numerically smaller of the two inputs (but keep it as a string),  
– and we print that string as many times as the numerically larger input indicates.  

All of the funny methods named I, ll, IIl, the `"".length()` calls, unreachable `return`s, unused `gcd`/`lcm`/`func` methods, and the massive obfuscated FastReader are just there to confuse you. The core loop is simply:
```java
if (N < M) {
  for (int i = 0; i < M; i++)
    s += nStr;
} else {
  for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
    s += mStr;
}
System.out.println(s);
```

That is the entire functionality.

This code really only does two things:

  1.  It provides an obfuscated “fast ­IO” wrapper (class Scan) for reading bytes, ints, longs, doubles and a single token‐string from System.in.

  2.  In main(), it reads one token (as a String), treats each character ‘B’ as a backspace (pop one character if the stack isn’t empty) and any other character as a normal character (push it onto the stack).  When it’s done scanning through the input it walks the stack (in insertion order) and prints out the characters that remain.

All of the weird static methods like lIl, llIl, IIl, IIIl, etc., and the nonsense calls to “” .length(), to arithmetic expressions in if-statements, etc., are purely there to break up the control flow and make the code harder to follow.  Underneath it’s exactly this:

    Scan sc = new Scan();
    String s = sc.scanString();
    Stack st = new Stack<>();
    for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
      if (c != 'B') {
        // normal character → push onto stack
        st.push(c);
      } else if (!st.isEmpty()) {
        // 'B' acts as a backspace → pop one character if possible
        st.pop();
      }
    }
    // collect what remains in the stack and print it
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
    for (Character c : st) {
      sb.append(c);
    }
    System.out.println(sb);

So if your input is

    ABCBD

you get:

    A → push
    B → pop A
    C → push
    B → pop C
    D → push

ending up with just “D” in the stack, which is printed.

This monstrous-looking class really only does one tiny thing in its `main` method.  All of the rest of the code is just a heavily‐obfuscated I/O library (with dead‐code injections like `“”.length()` and bogus ifs such as  
```java
if ((0xAC ^ 0xA8) < 0) return;
```  
that never trigger).

Here is the essence of `main` once you strip away the junk:

  1.  Read a whitespace‐delimited token `s` from standard in.
  2.  Test whether  
        s.charAt(2) == s.charAt(3)  
     **and**  
        s.charAt(4) == s.charAt(5)  
  3.  If both equalities hold, print “Yes”; otherwise print “No”.

That’s it.  All the static methods named `Il`, `IIl`, `Ill`, etc., and the endless try/catches and `“”.length()` calls are just noise.  Functionally it is equivalent to:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
  Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
  String s = in.next();
  if (s.charAt(2) == s.charAt(3) && s.charAt(4) == s.charAt(5)) {
    System.out.println("Yes");
  } else {
    System.out.println("No");
  }
}
```

Here is what the obfuscated program actually does once you peel away the junk code (the `“”.length()` calls, the always‐true or always‐false `if`/`return` blocks, etc.):

1. It reads an integer n.  
2. It reads an array p of length n from standard input.  
3. It then slides a window of size 3 over p (i.e. looks at every consecutive triple (p[i], p[i+1], p[i+2]) for i = 0 … n–3) and figures out which of the three is the median (middle) value.  
4. It keeps a counter cnt that it increments every time the middle element of the triple (p[i+1]) is in fact the median of the three values.  
5. Finally it prints cnt.

---

## How the obfuscation maps to normal comparisons

The five private static boolean methods are just renamings of the usual integer comparisons:

- I(n, m)    ⇔ n   m  
- ll(n, m)   ⇔ n ≠  m  
- IIl(n, m)  ⇔ n == m  

