     or `if ("".length() > " ".length()) return;`
   These conditions always evaluate to false, so they never alter control flow or output. They’re simply thrown in to confuse anyone reading the control flow.

3. Actual behavior:
   - Read an integer N from standard input.
   - If 0 ≤ N ≤ 1 000, print `1000 – N`.
   - Else if 1 000  10 000) print nothing.

In plain English, it tells you “how far you are from the next multiple of 1 000,” provided that next multiple is at most 10 000. All of the weird empty‐string checks and impossible `if`-conditions are just dead code injected to frustrate static readers.

This piece of code really boils down to two parts:

 1. A heavily‐obfuscated “FastScanner” class for fast I/O  
 2. A very simple calculation in the `main()` method that prints  
    (N/(A+B))×A + min(N%(A+B), A)

Everything else you see—methods called `l`, `ll`, `IIl`, random string‐length checks like `“”.length()`, empty branches, always‐false or always‐true `if`’s, throwing away return values—is purely dead‐code or trivial boolean wrappers meant to confuse a reader or thwart a decompiler.  None of it changes the real flow.

—————————————————————————————————————

1) FastScanner  
   • Wraps `System.in` in a 1 KB buffer.  
   • `hasNextByte()`, `readByte()` refill and read from the buffer.  
   • A bunch of tiny one‐liner methods (`l(int a,int b)` => `a`a`x!=0`, etc.) masquerade as comparisons.  
   • Useless lines like `“”.length();` or `if (null==null)` are always no‐ops or dead branches inserted at random.  
   • On top of that it implements `hasNext()`, `next()`, `nextLong()`, `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()` in the usual way:  
      – skip non‐printable bytes  
      – accumulate digits  
      – handle optional leading minus  
      – throw `NoSuchElementException` or `NumberFormatException` if input ends or is malformed  

   In short, this is just a fast scanner for whitespace‐separated tokens (ints, longs, strings, doubles) but wrapped in a layer of meaningless obfuscation.

2) Main logic  
   In `public class Main`:

     FastScanner fs = new FastScanner();
     long N = fs.nextLong();
     long A = fs.nextLong();
     long B = fs.nextLong();

     // Let one “cycle” be A active units, then B inactive units
     long cycle = A + B;
     // How many full cycles fit in N?
     long fullCycles = N / cycle;
     // In each full cycle we “get” A units of work
     long s = fullCycles * A;

     // Remainder after the full cycles
     long rem = N - fullCycles * cycle;

     // If the remainder is less than A, we only get rem more units,
     // otherwise we get the full A.
     if (rem < A) {
       s += rem;
     } else {
       s += A;
     }

     System.out.println(s);

In closed form the program computes:

   s = (N / (A + B)) * A  +  min( N % (A + B),  A )

and prints it.  

That’s the entire behavior. All of the extra private methods, weird `if` blocks, string‐length calls, inverted conditions, etc., are there purely to complicate control flow but do not alter this simple arithmetic.

