## Deobfuscated logic in pseudocode

```
// Read until no more numbers
while (scanner.hasNextLong()) {
  a = nextLong()
  b = nextLong()

  if (a > b) {
    // find smallest multiple of a that is divisible by b  → this is lcm(a,b)
    A = a
    while (A % b != 0) {
      A += a
    }
    L = A

    // compute gcd(a,b)
    if (a % b == 0) {
      g = b
    } else {
      // brute‐force: scan downward from b/2
      g = 1
      for (i = b/2; i > 0; i--) {
        if (a % i == 0 && b % i == 0) {
          g = i
          break
        }
      }
    }

    print(g, L)
  }
  else if (a  0; i--) {
        if (a % i == 0 && b % i == 0) {
          g = i
          break
        }
      }
    }

    print(g, L)
  }
  else {
    // a == b
    // gcd(a,a) = a, lcm(a,a) = a
    print(a, a)
  }
}
```

### What the tiny helper methods do

- `private static boolean I(int n)  { return n != 0; }`       → tests “true”  
- `private static boolean Il(int n) { return n == 0; }`       → tests “false”  
- `private static boolean l(int n)  { return n > 0; }`        → “positive”  
- `private static boolean ll(int n) { return n < 0; }`        → “negative”

All of the apparent complexity—labeled blocks, weird string‐length comparisons, nested pointless `return` statements—is purely to thwart a casual reader or a simplistic decompiler. Underneath it’s just a brute‐force GCD+LCM program.

The first thing to see is that all of the weirdly named methods in class hayami and the empty‐string calls and constant–XOR checks are pure noise—they don’t change the logic, they just force extra branches and dead‐code for the obfuscator.  If you strip away all of those, what you have is simply:

1. A small “fast I/O” class (hayami) that reads bytes from System.in into a buffer.
2. Methods to  
   • skip whitespace  
   • read the next token as a String  
   • parse the next token as a long  
   • parse the next token as an int (with range checking)  
   • parse the next token as a double  
   • close the stream  

