are simply hiding the obvious integer comparisons (`<`, `<=`, `==`, etc.).  The empty‐string `“”.length()` calls and nonsense `if ((0xB3^0xB7) <= " ".length()) …` are never true (or never false, depending on the branch) and exist solely to confuse a static analysis or a human reader.

Once you throw all of that away, the program in Main becomes:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
  hayami in = new hayami();

  // 1) read n
  int n = in.saori_hayami();

  // 2) read an array of n integers
  Integer[] a = new Integer[n];
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    a[i] = in.saori_hayami();
  }

  // 3) sort descending
  Arrays.sort(a, Collections.reverseOrder());

  // 4) form two sums: 
  //    num1 += elements at even indices (0,2,4,…)
  //    num2 += elements at odd indices  (1,3,5,…)
  int num1 = 0, num2 = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    if (i % 2 == 0) {
      num1 += a[i];
    } else {
      num2 += a[i];
    }
  }

  // 5) print the difference
  System.out.println(num1 - num2);

  in.close();
}
```

In plain English:

• Read an integer n  
• Read a list of n integers  
• Sort them in non‐increasing order  
• Take turns picking from the front of that sorted list:  
  – “Player 1” (even indices) accumulates num1  
  – “Player 2” (odd indices) accumulates num2  
• Print (num1 − num2)  

The supporting class hayami is just a heavily obfuscated but functionally standard buffered‐input helper; all of the control‐flow obfuscation is merely there to foil decompilers or human readers.

Let’s peel away all of the dead‐code‐injection and bogus ifs/length checks and look at the real meat of the program.  If you strip out:

  • the calls to `"".length()`  
