you end up with something extremely simple:

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
  FastReader in = new FastReader(System.in);
  int n = in.nextInt();

  // arr holds the input permutation
  int[] arr = new int[n];
  // io will hold the inverse permutation
  int[] io  = new int[n];

  // read the permutation and build its inverse
  for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
    arr[i] = in.nextInt();        // a value from 1..n
    io[ arr[i] - 1 ] = i + 1;     // store the 1‐based position of that value
  }

  // print the inverse
  for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
    System.out.print(io[i] + " ");
  }
}
```

In other words, the program:

1. Reads an integer n.  
2. Reads a permutation of {1,2,…,n} into `arr[0..n−1]`.  
3. Constructs `io` so that `io[k]` = the position (1-based) in the input of the element k+1.  
4. Prints out `io[0] io[1] … io[n−1]`, i.e. the inverse permutation.

All of the extra boolean‐named methods (`I()`, `Il()`, `lIl()`, etc.), the dead‐string‐length hacks, and the weird ifs are just obfuscation.  The real functionality is “compute and print the inverse of an input permutation.”
